This might be hard to believe, but the number one question posed to me is not about outfits, prints or posing...it’s about timing 📅⁣ 

“When the heck am I supposed to take my senior pictures?!” 

Or the even more common:

“Wait, why didn’t I start planning this earlier?! Is it too late?”
⁣
If you haven’t noticed, senior year gets busy QUICKLY — college applications, stacked sporting events, and a lengthy list of ‘lasts’...⁣
⁣
So what exactly determines the ‘best’ month for one of the most important milestones of all — your senior photo session?!⁣
⁣
The honest truth is...there are hardly any ‘bad’ months (depending on your area) So, it really depends on what’s important to YOU!⁣
⁣
Here are the 3 primary factors to consider when choosing your session date:⁣
⁣
1) COLLEGE CHOICE 🏈 if you want to rep your soon-to-be hometown during your session, then you gotta know where you’re goin’ first! While some students commit the fall of their senior year, most do so in April. Your best months: MAR, APR, MAY⁣
⁣
2) DEADLINES 📔 Yearbooks often require your portrait submissions in the winter, and your calendar will be bustling with grad party invites come June. If you want professional photos in your yearbook, aim for SEP, OCT, NOV. If you want plenty of time before your grad party to order super cute products with your face on ‘em, shoot no later than APR to be safe.⁣
⁣
3) SEASONAL PREFERENCE 🍂 Do you picture yourself bundled in a winter outfit in a cute local coffee shop, or are you game to splash in your local lakes or oceans? If you like warm neutrals, OCT is the month for you. If you want spring greens, aim for MARCH.⁣
⁣
That being said, no matter the month, the BEST way to prepare for your session is to a) plan ahead and b) go into it with an up-for-anything attitude!⁣
⁣
For more information about senior sessions, feel free to pop on over to the link in my bio. Happy senior-ing!

Here’s why you need to collect and review client feedback in your photography business (and a few crazy-easy ways to do it):⁣
⁣
WHY:⁣
🧭 Feedback is the easiest way to make small adjustments in your business to improve the client experience. Changing the course of your business by just one degree will completely shift your goal destination. Use each and every review, text or email as a way to get 1% better in your business.⁣
❤️ Client experience is everything! Knowing what made your recent client’s experience unique equips you with valuable talking points for your future clientele.⁣
🥳 It feels good! Sometimes as solopreneurs, photographers don’t often get pats on the back from our ‘co-workers’ or promotions to give us a sense of accomplishment. Reviewing positive feedback is one of my favorite ways to celebrate a job well done!⁣
⁣
But HOW do you get it? ⁣
⁣
Photographers know the running joke of delivering a gallery and the agony of not receiving an immediate, all-caps happy-screaming message back. ⁣
⁣
Silence can feel LOUD, can’t it?⁣
⁣
But before jumping to the conclusion that no news is bad news, ask yourself — did you yourself ASK for feedback?⁣
⁣
The way I see it, we’ve got to put ourselves in the client’s shoes. When I get photos done, for example, I dive SO quickly into that gallery, downloading, ooh-ing and aah-ing at the results, that even I have to remind myself, “Oh shoot! Let me send my photographer a message letting her know what I loved about my experience!”
⁣
Sometimes it’s as easy as:⁣ 

1️⃣ asking for a review AT the photo session⁣
2️⃣ including your review links in the gallery delivery email⁣
3️⃣ following up with a client experience feedback questionnaire via Google forms, Typeform, or your CRM software (I use @honeybook )
⁣
Oh, and pro tip - screenshot your rave reviews and store it in a folder on your phone or computer. You never know when it might come in handy for content or marketing materials!⁣
⁣

This year let’s opt out of the one-way-ticket down the ‘outfit inspo’ rabbit-hole that, frankly, I know you don’t have time to go down.

As a believer in the “teach a man how to fish” philosophy, whenever I get asked this FAQ in preparation for a family photo session—

“But what will I wear?!” (a la grinch)

— I make sure NOT to just hand over the fish. 

Here are 4 superfood ingredients you’ll need to build your own family outfit ✨menu✨ if you will:

ingredient 1 // THE PRIMARY ‘FIT ❤️

This is usually mom, or whoever is planning the session.

Be selfish, choose a piece that makes YOU feel like a billion bucks before worrying about anyone else.

I recommend a long-ish dress with fabric that moves.

ingredient 2 // THE SECONDARY COLOR 💙

Grab the nearest color wheel (a quick google search will do) and hop across the color of your primary color to choose the palette’s complementary color.

Doesn’t have to be exact. Example: in this video, the primary is red. The cross color would be green, but the Jeffersons opted for a neighboring blue.

This is where you start to add in kids’ pieces.

ingredient 3// CHOOSE A NEUTRAL 🤎

Before we go wild with red and blue, let’s tame it down with a neutral.

This is a great place to add in pants, like gray, khaki or tan.

ingredient 4 // ADD A LIFT 🤍

If you’re Plankton, & I’m Spongebob (sorry) and you want the secret recipe to the krabby patty and well, THIS IS IT: 

Don’t stop at adding in a neutral. Add in light cream color throughout, as well, just not in a bright white.

Why? This « lifts » the palette to be brighter and less visually weighted.

& it’s not what you might think

The difference between introducing yourself as a photographer and someone who owns a photography business may seem trivial…

But even the tiniest degree of difference in positioning, over time, will dramatically change the course of your life and business.

The difference is NOT that

❌ One has employees
❌ One has more experience
❌ One posts to more followers
❌ One generates more revenue

These static snapshots may measure current position..but relative to what path?

✅ You see, a photography business owner knows that the most important determinant of success is that which is in motion. Kinetic. Mobile. On-the-move, baby! 

Think about going on a road trip. You have the car, and it’s full of gas. Snacks are stocked. They keys are in the ignition, and you roll out of the lot onto the open road. You should be good to go, right?

Well, that depends — are you going to take a road trip without GPS? Or at least a map? 

Think of it this way: the photographer is the passenger, enjoying the ride and looking out at the views as they roll by.

The photography business owner is behind the wheel, doing the very same, but is fully aware of the path ahead, and correcting the course constantly.

If you’re feeling like the passenger, waking up from your nap and thinking, “Dang, are we already in Barstow?” 

Then it’s time to jump into the driver’s seat, my friend. 

Knowing your route means you can get to your destination safely and on time, and more importantly — that you can stop worrying about the paths of everyone else while you’re well on your way.
